snippet.textDisplay:
The GameStop thing is due to the people that shorted it did so to such a degree that there are more short sales than there is stock available to cover the shorts. The price is going up because the short sellers cannot buy any stock at a reasonable price and they HAVE TO BUY it eventually.

A short sell is a bet that the stock is going to go down, so you borrow stock to sell and then buy stock back to cover the sale and make a profit on the difference in price IF IT GOES LOWER. If it goes up then there is a loss. This is usually not a disaster because you can at least minimize your loss before it gets too bad.

Only in this case there isn't enough stock available AT ANY PRICE to cover all the shorts.

The Bears are taking a major beating.

snippet.textDisplay: Correction - the massive rise in the GameStop stock price is actually due to a short squeeze - basically some hedge funds predicted they would go bust, borrowed a bunch of shares and sold them with the intent of buying them back later for nothing to pay them back and turn a profit (short selling). The issue is they shorted so many shares that they would up obliged to pay back more shares than are available, so when WSB realised this they bought a ton of GameStop shares, which didn't just increase demand directly but also took shares out of circulation right as the short sellers were forced to buy, resulting in an immense explosion in demand because the hedge funds have no choice and must buy them. That is, the WSB Redditors found a huge mistake that the big hedge funds made and were able to make a ton of money as a result.

jacking up the stock value.  Anyone making a gain out of that will be 
making that gain on the backs of others who got out too late and lost.
